    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1980-01-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1980-01-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="166"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d166">
                <head>166. Memorandum From the Director for Operations, Joint Chiefs of Staff
                        (<persName corresp="#p_SPD_1">Shutler</persName>), to the Chairman of the
                    Joint Chiefs of Staff (<persName corresp="#p_JDC_1">Jones</persName>)<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d166fn1">Source: Department of Defense, Joint Chiefs
                        of Staff Records, <gloss target="#t_RG_1">RG</gloss> 218–98–0064, Records of
                        J–3 <gloss target="#t_DDSO_1">DDSO</gloss>, Box 1, DOD Intel Experience
                        (Iran Hostage Rescue). Top Secret; Eyes Only.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1980-01-28">January 28, 1980</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Conditions for Hostage Rescue Attempt</item>
                </list>
                <p>1. (<gloss target="#t_TS_1">TS</gloss>) The attached paper by the <gloss
                        target="#t_JTF_1">JTF</gloss> explores the factors affecting a decision to
                    rescue the hostages. The summary on page 8 gives a good thumbnail sketch of the
                        analysis.<note n="2" xml:id="d166fn2">The January 25 untitled paper is
                        attached but not printed; the summary is printed as <ref target="#d167"
                            >Document 167</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>2. (<gloss target="#t_TS_1">TS</gloss>) It appears to me that three external
                    conditions can apply:</p>
                <quote>
                    <p>a. Hostages secure. Negotiations continuing as at present.</p>
                    <p>b. Hostages gravely threatened by current captors, other competing
                        politically oriented terrorist organizations, or mob action during
                        chaos.</p>
                    <p>c. One or more hostages injured or killed.</p>
                </quote>
                <p>3. (<gloss target="#t_TS_1">TS</gloss>) The odds on success (60–70% in execution
                    tempered by 15–30% possibility of disruption) do not appear to be high enough to
                    warrant an attempt under current conditions. If we wait until hostages have been
                    injured or killed, the pressure to act will be so high, and the situation in
                    Iran so uncertain, that the odds for success would certainly be drastically
                    reduced. The hard part will be to recognize a time of increased danger and to
                    act accordingly. The team is continuing to refine plans to deploy, in particular
                    to get to the shortest response time consistent with operational security. [<hi
                        rend="italic">4 lines not declassified</hi>]</p>
                <p>Very respectfully,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SPD_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Philip D. Shutler</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Lieutenant General, USMC <lb/> Director for
                            Operations</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
